Data.TextValue:
Dit project moet nog worden aangepast. Je moet met de %iProtect_keykeygroup_id% het lidmaatschap in iprotect ontnemen (combinatie keygroup en accesskey). Want als je in AD niet lid bent van de keygroup, moeten de rechten op de passen in iprotect worden ontnomen. Maar dit kan pas wanneer alle autorisaties worden toegekend in AD, via een rol of direcht op de GG_SEC_IPR_ groeplidmaatschappen... Zo lang FrontOffice in iProtect rechten blijft uitdelen, zal deze functie de dag er na de rechten in iprotect weer intrekken.
Daarom draait er tijdelijk een andere functionaliteit hier, welke dus het handmatige toegevoegde recht in iprotect -> overheveld naar de AD keygroup. De user wordt dus gekoppeld in AD.
Als frontoffice dus umra gaat gebruiken om autorisaties in iprotect te zetten, kan dit project worden aangepast. Simpel weg: wat nu uitgecommentarieerd is, moet dan geactiveerd worden (eerst testen).
Front Office moet dan weten dat ELKE wijziging op een pas met personeelsnummer in iProtect door umra de volgende nacht wordt ingetrokken... Je MOET lid zijn in AD van een GG_SEC_IPR_ groep om in iprotect een recht te krijgen op een keygroup.
Nu is dat nog niet het geval.

Base.Explanation: Searches the Active Directory for one or more objects. For each object found, the object distinguished name is returned. For the search, you need to specify the environment (LDAP, GC, domain, ou, etc.) and the LDAP search string.

ArrayElement.Name: Search environment
ArrayElement.Description: The search is performed in one of three possible environment: LDAP, GC or any other object. To search the entire Active Directory environment accessible from the local computer, specify the word LDAP (1). To search in the Global Catalog, specify the word GC (2). To search in any other environment, specify the LDAP binding string to access the object (3). Example: To search in a specify domain: LDAP://domain or LDAP://host. To search in a specific OU: LDAP://domaincontroller/OU=students,DC=domain,DC=com.

ArrayElement.Name: LDAP search Filter
ArrayElement.Description: The LDAP search filter according to RFC 2254. Example, to find user accounts with a specific description field 1234: (&(objectClass=user) (&(description=1234))

ArrayElement.Name: Error if nothing found
ArrayElement.Description: Generate an error for this script action if no matching objects are found.

ArrayElement.Name: Error if multiple found
ArrayElement.Description: Generate an error for this script action if multiple matching objects are found.

ArrayElement.Name: Search in child objects
ArrayElement.Description: Search in the specified environment and child objects, for example child domains.

ArrayElement.Name: Number of objects found
ArrayElement.Description: The number of matching objects found. This property is an 'output only' property and is generated by the application automatically. By default, the value for this property is stored in variable %SearchResultCount%.

ArrayElement.Name: Object distinguished names
ArrayElement.Description: The distinguished names of the matching objects. This property is an 'output only' property and is generated by the application automatically. By default, the value for this property is stored in variable %SearchResults%.

Base.Explanation: Set the group memberships for Active Directory object. The Active Directory object can be any object that can become a member of the specified groups, e.g. a user, other group, contact etc. The Active Directory object can be specified by a variable or an object distinguished name.

ArrayElement.Name: Active Directory Object
ArrayElement.Description: A data structure representing the Active Directory object for which the group membership is updated. To specify the object, you must use this property or property 'Active Directory LDAP name'. If you use this property you must specify a variable for which the value is generated by another action.

ArrayElement.Name: Active Directory name
ArrayElement.Description: The name of the Active Directory object for which the group membership is updated. To specify the object, you must use this property or property 'Active Directory Object'. If you use this property you must specify the object disinghuised name of the Active Directory object. Example: cn=Group123,ou=Ou32,dc=tools4ever,dc=com.

ArrayElement.Name: Group names (variable)
ArrayElement.Description: The names of the groups of which the Active Directory object must become a member. Each group name must be specified by its full LDAP name. The value of this property can only be specified by a multi-text variable.

Base.Explanation: Remove keyGroup membership for an accessKey.

Base.Name: Session ID
Base.Description: This parameter identifies the Powershell Agent service session.

Base.Name: iProtect webservice url
Base.Description: The address of the iProtect webservice. (https://server:8443/Webcontrols/)

Base.Name: KEYKEYGROUP_KEYKEYGROUPID
Base.Description: KEYKEYGROUP_KEYKEYGROUPID, this value can be extracted using the 'List keyGroup memberships (iProtect)' dynamic action.

Base.Name: retVal
Base.Description: This will be 0 when the action executes successfully. If an error occured during execution, the value will be 1.
